# Cursor Rules for Capstone Grade Analyze Project

## Code Quality & Professional Standards

### General Principles
- Write clean, readable, and maintainable code
- Follow SOLID principles and clean architecture patterns
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Write self-documenting code with clear intent
- Implement proper error handling and validation
- Optimize for performance and scalability

### No Emojis in Code
- **STRICTLY PROHIBITED**: No emojis, symbols, or decorative characters in code
- Use clear, descriptive text instead of visual symbols
- Keep code professional and business-appropriate
- Use standard ASCII characters only

### Code Style & Formatting
- Use consistent indentation (2 spaces for JS/TS, 4 spaces for Python)
- Follow language-specific style guides (ESLint for JS/TS, Black for Python)
- Use meaningful comments that explain "why" not "what"
- Keep functions small and focused (max 20-30 lines)
- Use TypeScript strict mode for type safety

### Performance Optimization
- Implement efficient algorithms and data structures
- Use caching strategies where appropriate
- Optimize database queries and API calls
- Minimize bundle size and loading times
- Use lazy loading for components and modules
- Implement proper pagination for large datasets

### Security Best Practices
- Validate all user inputs on both client and server
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Implement proper authentication and authorization
- Sanitize data before storing or displaying
- Use HTTPS for all communications
- Implement rate limiting and CORS policies
- Store sensitive data securely (environment variables)
- Regular security audits and dependency updates

### ML Service Specific Rules
- Use type hints for all Python functions
- Implement proper error handling for ML model failures
- Use async/await for I/O operations
- Implement request timeout handling
- Use proper logging instead of print statements
- Validate input data before ML processing
- Implement graceful degradation when models fail

### Frontend Specific Rules
- Use React best practices (hooks, functional components)
- Implement proper state management
- Use TypeScript for type safety
- Implement responsive design principles
- Use semantic HTML and accessibility standards
- Optimize images and assets
- Implement proper loading states and error boundaries

### Database & API Rules
- Use proper database indexing
- Implement connection pooling
- Use transactions for data consistency
- Implement proper API versioning
- Use RESTful API design principles
- Implement proper HTTP status codes
- Use proper data serialization/deserialization

### Testing & Quality Assurance
- Write unit tests for critical functions
- Implement integration tests for API endpoints
- Use proper test data and mocking
- Test edge cases and error conditions
- Implement continuous integration checks
- Use code coverage tools

### Documentation Standards
- Write clear README files
- Document API endpoints with examples
- Use JSDoc for JavaScript/TypeScript functions
- Use docstrings for Python functions
- Keep documentation up-to-date with code changes

### Git & Version Control
- Use meaningful commit messages
- Create feature branches for new development
- Use pull requests for code review
- Keep commits atomic and focused
- Use conventional commit format

### Monitoring & Logging
- Implement proper logging levels (DEBUG, INFO, WARN, ERROR)
- Use structured logging (JSON format)
- Monitor application performance
- Implement health checks
- Use proper log rotation and retention

### Error Handling
- Use try-catch blocks appropriately
- Implement graceful error recovery
- Provide meaningful error messages to users
- Log errors for debugging
- Use proper HTTP status codes
- Implement circuit breaker patterns for external services

### Code Review Checklist
- [ ] No emojis or decorative characters
- [ ] Clean, readable code structure
- [ ] Proper error handling implemented
- [ ] Security best practices followed
- [ ] Performance optimizations applied
- [ ] Tests written and passing
